Organization = {Inst Escola Super Design; ID+ Res Inst Design Media \& Culture;
   Santander Univ; NORPRINT; Camara Municipal Esposende; Mestado Ilustracao
   Animacao; Viarco; Minist Educacao Ciencia, Fundacao Ciencia Tecnologia},
Abstract = {Japanese animation acquired its key features in the 1960s, when it was
   established as an industry. However, the aesthetic qualities of the
   drawings and the richness of their fabulous stories began to be
   appreciated even before the appearance of the term manga, when images
   started to emerge with characteristics that would eventually form the
   basis of the visual language of the current anime: stylized drawing and
   sequential image. For this reason, and in order to understand anime as
   we know it today, it is necessary to investigate its hidden history and
   origins, beyond famous animation studios or consecrated animators. This
   article explores the traditional Japanese art forms from the first
   caricature-like drawings to the animation creations that appeared at the
   beginning of the twentieth century.},
